The Kogi State government has advised workers to brace up for tough times ahead as it commenced the payment of their March salaries. Mukadam Asiwaju Asiru Idris, the commissioner for Finance, Budget and Economic Planning, made the disclosure to newsmen in Lokoja, yesterday. He said despite the shortfall in the monthly allocation to the state, the Yahaya Bello administration has demonstrated its commitment to workers’ welfare by paying their full salaries. Idris said that the shortfall was occasioned by the COVID-19 scourge now ravaging the world, stating that the pandemic alongside the ensuing austerity measures owing to the fall in oil prices, called for retrospection amongst the citizens. While observing that oil, which is the nation’s main source of revenue now sells for $20 in the global market, the commissioner expressed fears of economically gloomy months ahead. He explained that as from 1st April, Saudi Arabia, which is an oil-producing competitor with Nigeria, will sell Arab Light at $10.25 per barrel discount to Dated Brent. Similarly, he expressed more worries that Kuwait dropped $7 of its prices to NW Europe ; Iraq dropped $4 of its price to Europe and Iran dropped $6 of its price for April Cargoes to Europe. It means that tougher times lay ahead for the economy. In his words, “the shock has amplified the epic battle between Russia and Saudi Arabia. First, Russia refused to cut production despite the obvious need for less supply. That refusal is driven by its desire to drown high-cost US producers in a sea of cheap crude in hopes of recapturing market share. On what his advice is to the citizens, particularly workers in this period of austerity, Idris urged them to invest wisely, particularly on issues of education, health and feeding, advising against embarking on gigantic projects that do not  have direct bearing on the lives of their  people.